Level-0 Motion: This House Supports a decline in global reliance on the dollar., Side: for
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Global reliance on the dollar is detrimental to the world economy because it creates systemic risk and restricts countries' ability to implement effective economic policies.", "argument": ["Creates systemic risk due to the US financial sector's instability.", "Restricts countries' ability to implement effective economic policies by forcing them to follow US monetary policy.", "Dollar is the primary reserve currency.", "Dollar is the dominant currency for lending.", "Many nations peg their own currency to the dollar.", "This system is often imposed, limiting monetary sovereignty, especially for developing nations.", "Diversification allows hedging against US financial instability.", "Tailored responses foster investor confidence in emerging markets.", "Different countries have different economic strategies.", "Dollar dominance forces countries to follow US monetary policy.", "Following US policy can be detrimental to other economies.", "Autonomy attracts foreign investment.", "Autonomy maintains price stability.", "Autonomy provides essential services.", "Autonomy improves quality of life.", "The current system disproportionately benefits the US.", "It ensures cheap borrowing.", "It ensures strong equity markets.", "It ensures a sustained trade deficit without inflationary consequences.", "This is due to constant demand for dollars.", "Shifting away from dollar dominance redistributes benefits.", "This potentially boosts economies like the EU and Japan, or even China.", "This increases global competition and development.", "Reduced reliance on the dollar allows countries to prioritize domestic spending.", "This stimulates their own economies.", "US dollar dominance hinders global development.", "Shifting away from dollar dominance would distribute financial benefits more fairly.", "The focus is on decentralization, not choosing a specific alternative currency.", "Trillions of dollars are at stake, with half of US-denominated foreign debt held by foreign actors.", "Redirecting this capital would significantly stimulate other economies.", "Wealthier nations are increasingly investing domestically.", "This trend signals a shift away from dollar dominance.", "This shift fuels development in other regions.", "Redistribution empowers local governments by providing greater resources for fiscal policy.", "Increased access to domestic capital promotes stability and democratization.", "Countries become less vulnerable to external shocks.", "Lower borrowing rates for businesses.", "Facilitation of entrepreneurship.", "Promotion of local economic growth.", "Equitable distribution of capital allows governments to prioritize development over military spending.", "Marginal utility of capital is higher in poorer nations."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "The dollar remains the best global reserve currency due to the US's stable economy, robust democratic institutions, and transparent political system.", "argument": ["The US has a diversified economy.", "The US has robust democratic institutions.", "The US has a transparent political system, providing predictability.", "The US system can adapt and reform, as shown post-2008.", "Authoritarian regimes like China and Russia have opaque decision-making, creating volatility.", "The EU lacks the cohesive fiscal control of the US.", "The dollar's stability is partly a self-fulfilling prophecy due to the US economy's size.", "The US, with its democratic mechanisms, is the best candidate for a single global currency.", "The dollar's strength allows the US to navigate crises effectively through fiscal stimulus.", "This ability to borrow and stimulate allows the US to recover quickly from recessions."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "Domestic financial conditions, not just reserves, are more impactful on stability.", "argument": ["A nation's ability to moderate its currency depends on its ability to buy and sell reserves.", "Domestic financial conditions are more impactful on stability than reserves."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Current economic challenges stem from global events like the pandemic and the war in Ukraine, not the dollar's strength.", "argument": ["The pandemic and the war in Ukraine are the cause of current economic challenges."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "US financial regulations have improved significantly since 2008, and a deregulated market encourages competition, preventing oligopolies.", "argument": ["US financial regulations have improved significantly since 2008 (Dodd-Frank).", "A deregulated market encourages competition.", "A deregulated market prevents the emergence of oligopolies.", "China's financial system is dangerously tied to a volatile housing market."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "A Chinese-led system is no more predictable or less dangerous than the current US-led system.", "argument": ["The government highlights the uncertainty of future US actions.", "The government fails to explain why a Chinese-led system is any more predictable or less dangerous."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "A basket of reserve currencies exacerbates regional inequalities, harming smaller countries.", "argument": ["Benefits are unlikely to reach developing nations.", "Strong economies are more attractive reserve options.", "Weaker economies are left vulnerable.", "The government's proposal risks exacerbating regional inequalities.", "Smaller countries are harmed more than in a US-centric system.", "Long-term adaptation negates any supposed benefits."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "The US will likely resort to coercive measures if the dollar declines.", "argument": ["The US will not passively accept the decline of the dollar.", "The US will likely resort to coercive measures like sanctions and diplomatic pressure."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "China's economic competition involves vast subsidies and a state-controlled banking system, creating a dangerous bipolar world.", "argument": ["China can offer vast subsidies.", "China has a state-controlled banking system.", "This gives China a distinct advantage in economic competition.", "This coercion is the most immediate and least mitigatable consequence.", "A powerful actor manipulating the system creates a far greater threat.", "This coercion undermines the agency of smaller nations.", "This creates a dangerous bipolar world.", "A bipolar system weakens sanctions, incentivizes Chinese aggression, and hinders international cooperation.", "This leads to a less stable and more dangerous world."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "The dollar's dominance limits monetary sovereignty by acting as the primary reserve currency, the dominant currency for lending, and the currency to which many nations peg their own.", "argument": ["Dollar is the primary reserve currency.", "Dollar is the dominant currency for lending.", "Many nations peg their own currency to the dollar.", "This system is often imposed, limiting monetary sovereignty, especially for developing nations.", "The current system forces developing economies to prioritize dollar acquisition.", "This redirects trade towards the US.", "This necessitates holding large dollar reserves.", "This influences loan decisions.", "Dollar dominance reinforces the power of the IMF and World Bank.", "These institutions often push neoliberal policies.", "These policies prioritize exports to the US at the expense of local industry.", "Dollar dominance incentivizes skilled labor migration to the US.", "This deprives developing nations of human capital."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "A diversified system allows countries to hedge against US-centric financial instability and tailor their responses, fostering investor confidence in emerging markets.", "argument": ["Diversification allows hedging against US financial instability.", "Tailored responses foster investor confidence in emerging markets.", "Our proposal allows for more diverse reserve holdings.", "This reflects actual trade relationships.", "This promotes greater economic autonomy."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "A single reserve currency, the dollar, is superior to a fragmented basket of currencies because it facilitates smoother international trade and promotes economic growth.", "argument": ["A fragmented system increases transaction costs.", "A fragmented system hinders free trade.", "A fragmented system diminishes comparative advantages between nations.", "Nations exploring alternatives undermine global economic efficiency.", "A unified system under the dollar facilitates smoother international trade.", "A unified system under the dollar promotes economic growth."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "Trading with a basket of currencies requires multiple conversions, negating any supposed efficiency.", "argument": ["Trading with a basket of currencies requires multiple conversions.", "This negates any supposed efficiency."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "A stable currency like the dollar provides a crucial benchmark for global trade, simplifying currency management and ensuring predictability in currency markets.", "argument": ["The dollar provides a stable benchmark for global trade.", "It simplifies currency management compared to a fluctuating basket.", "Predictability in currency markets is essential for trade.", "Unstable reserve currencies complicate trade and discourage it, especially for developing economies."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "The dollar's dominance facilitates trade between countries, even those with strained relations with the US, by serving as a common denominator.", "argument": ["The dollar facilitates trade between any two countries holding dollar reserves.", "Even countries under US sanctions, like Russia, hold dollar reserves.", "The dollar serves as a common denominator for trade between countries like Zambia and Rwanda.", "A basket system makes this significantly more difficult."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Diversification is ineffective when economies are intertwined, and the US has mechanisms to recover from recessions, unlike a basket system.", "argument": ["Diversification is not effective when economies are intertwined.", "A crisis in the US often impacts the Eurozone due to their interconnectedness.", "The US has mechanisms to recover from recessions.", "This safety net is absent in a basket system."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "A basket of reserve currencies is impractical due to high costs and complexity.", "argument": ["Constant shifting between currencies is impractical.", "High costs and complexity of managing multiple trading and payment systems.", "Limits the agency of smaller nations."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "A basket of reserve currencies introduces instability, hindering economic development.", "argument": ["A basket of reserve currencies introduces instability.", "Investments become risky.", "Economic development is hindered.", "This insecurity undermines the government's entire premise."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "US economic policies often conflict with the needs of other nations, forcing them to follow US monetary policy even when it's detrimental to their own economies.", "argument": ["Different countries have different economic strategies.", "Dollar dominance forces countries to follow US monetary policy.", "Following US policy can be detrimental to other economies."]}
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "Autonomy in monetary policy is crucial for attracting foreign investment, maintaining price stability, and providing essential services, ultimately improving quality of life.", "argument": ["Autonomy attracts foreign investment.", "Autonomy maintains price stability.", "Autonomy provides essential services.", "Autonomy improves quality of life."]}

